; ----------------------------------------------------------------
; Cisco feature dialplan for asterisk-pjsip-cisco
; ----------------------------------------------------------------
;
; Most Cisco feature behaviour (Confrn / ConfList / Join / Select /
; Unselect / RmLastConf / Mute / Remove / Update / HLog / MCID / DND
; / CFwdALL / HuntGroup / Record / Park) is driven by native
; softkeys handled by the cisco_* modules; no dialplan is required
; for the softkeys themselves to work.
;
; This sample covers two things:
;
;   1) PARK — required wiring of res_parking into the cisco-features
;      context so the RemoteCC Park softkey lands in a real lot.
;
;   2) CISCO_* dialplan-function recipes — optional, only when you
;      want to make dialplan-side routing decisions based on the
;      DND / HuntGroup / CFwdAll state the softkeys manage.
;
; To use: paste this file into /etc/asterisk/extensions.conf (or
; #include it), then either set
;     context = cisco-features
; on each Cisco endpoint in pjsip.conf, or add
;     include => cisco-features
; to the endpoint's existing dialplan context.
;
; ----------------------------------------------------------------
; PARK — extension 700, slots 701-720 (defaults)
; ----------------------------------------------------------------
; The RemoteCC Park / ParkMonitor softkey (res_pjsip_cisco_remotecc)
; blind-transfers the peer to <parkext>@<the parker's context> —
; parkext defaults to 700 and is overridable per endpoint via
; `parkext=` on the type=cisco object. That target needs to resolve
; to res_parking's Park() application, which is the role of this
; sample.
;
; Verify res_parking is configured:  asterisk -rx 'parking show'
; If no lot is listed, add one to /etc/asterisk/res_parking.conf:
;   [general]
;   [default]
;   parkext     => 700
;   parkpos     => 701-720
;   context     => parkedcalls
;   parkingtime => 45
;   comebacktoorigin => yes
; (and confirm modules.conf does NOT noload res_parking).
;
; Make 700 + 701-720 reachable from this context. `include =>
; parkedcalls` does it — UNLESS this context also has a broad
; catch-all (e.g. `_X.`): Asterisk consults included contexts only
; AFTER the current context's own patterns, so the catch-all would
; shadow the include. In that case claim the range explicitly with
; patterns that out-rank `_X.`:
;   exten => _70[0-9],1,Goto(parkedcalls,${EXTEN},1)
;   exten => _71[0-9],1,Goto(parkedcalls,${EXTEN},1)
;   exten => 720,1,Goto(parkedcalls,720,1)

[cisco-features]

include => parkedcalls


; ----------------------------------------------------------------
; CISCO_* dialplan-function recipes (OPTIONAL)
; ----------------------------------------------------------------
; The cisco_bulkupdate module exposes three dialplan functions:
;
;   CISCO_DND(<endpoint>)           — read returns "YES" / "";
;                                     write toggles DND state + refreshes
;                                     the phone's DND lamp via REFER.
;   CISCO_HUNTGROUP(<endpoint>)     — read returns "YES" / "";
;                                     write toggles in/out-of-group state +
;                                     refreshes the phone's HLog softkey.
;   CISCO_CALLFORWARD(<endpoint>)   — read returns the forward target
;                                     (empty when CFwd is off); write sets
;                                     the target + refreshes the phone's
;                                     CFwdAll lamp.
;
; Setting these from dialplan updates the state on the phone UI.
; They do NOT install server-side routing. If you want incoming
; calls to a DND'd or CFwd'd extension to be routed differently in
; dialplan, you have to wire that yourself — the recipes below show
; the standard patterns.
;
; Server-side capture of phone-side softkey input is asymmetric:
;
;   DND softkey       — captured server-side; the PUBLISH the phone
;                       sends is handled by res_pjsip_cisco_feature_events,
;                       which calls cisco_dnd_set() for you. No
;                       dialplan needed for DND to persist.
;   HLog softkey      — captured server-side; the REFER the phone
;                       sends is handled by res_pjsip_cisco_remotecc,
;                       which calls cisco_huntgroup_set() for you. No
;                       dialplan needed for HuntGroup to persist.
;   CFwdAll softkey   — NOT captured server-side. The phone INVITEs
;                       a service-URI when the user enters / cancels
;                       the forward target, and dialplan has to catch
;                       that INVITE and write CISCO_CALLFORWARD itself
;                       (Recipe 1). Without this wiring, pressing
;                       CFwdAll on the phone does nothing visible to
;                       Asterisk.
;
; ----------------------------------------------------------------
; Recipe 1 — Capture CFwdAll softkey input  (REQUIRED for CFwd save)
; ----------------------------------------------------------------
; When the user enters a forward target via the CFwdAll softkey,
; the phone INVITEs `x--serviceuri-cfwdall-<target>@<context>`.
; When they cancel, it INVITEs `x--serviceuri-cfwdall-@<context>`
; (empty target). Catch both patterns and Set CISCO_CALLFORWARD
; for the calling endpoint:
;
;   exten => _x--serviceuri-cfwdall-X.,1,Answer()
;    same => n,Set(CISCO_CALLFORWARD(${CHANNEL(endpoint)})=${EXTEN:22})
;    same => n,Hangup()
;
;   exten => x--serviceuri-cfwdall-,1,Answer()
;    same => n,Set(CISCO_CALLFORWARD(${CHANNEL(endpoint)})=)
;    same => n,Hangup()
;
; - ${CHANNEL(endpoint)} is the calling Cisco endpoint's name, so
;   this recipe works for every phone without per-line duplication.
; - ${EXTEN:22} strips the 22-char "x--serviceuri-cfwdall-" prefix
;   to leave just the dialed target.
; - Answer() before Set() so the phone considers the action
;   accepted; without it the softkey UI shows the change as
;   pending or fails. The bulkupdate REFER fires from the Set()
;   itself, so the CFwdAll banner on the phone updates the moment
;   the dialplan completes.
;
; To verify the exact pattern your firmware sends, run
; `pjsip set logger on`, press CFwdAll on a phone, and observe the
; INVITE Request-URI. The patterns above match Enterprise SIP 9.x
; through 14.x on the 7975 / 8845 / 8861 / 8865 — older firmwares
; may differ.
;
; ----------------------------------------------------------------
; Recipe 2 — DND-aware Dial
; ----------------------------------------------------------------
; Skip the Dial leg entirely (no ring, no missed-call notification
; on the phone screen) when the target endpoint is on DND. Cheaper
; than letting the phone ring and 486-Busy the INVITE, and lets you
; deliver a different greeting / route to a coverage queue.
;
;   exten => _6XXX,1,GotoIf($["${CISCO_DND(${EXTEN})}" = "YES"]?on-dnd)
;    same => n,Dial(PJSIP/${EXTEN},30)
;    same => n,Voicemail(${EXTEN}@default,u)
;    same => n,Hangup()
;    same => n(on-dnd),Voicemail(${EXTEN}@default,b)
;    same => n,Hangup()
;
; Use ,b on the DND branch so the caller hears the "busy" greeting
; rather than the "unavailable" one; signals to the caller that the
; user is reachable but not taking calls right now.
;
; ----------------------------------------------------------------
; Recipe 3 — CFwdAll-honoring Dial  (REQUIRED for CFwd to redirect)
; ----------------------------------------------------------------
; Setting CFwdAll on the phone (softkey or CISCO_CALLFORWARD write)
; updates the phone's UI but does NOT add a server-side 302 redirect.
; If you want calls to actually be forwarded to the CFwd target,
; read CISCO_CALLFORWARD in the routing dialplan and Dial that
; target instead of the user.
;
;   exten => _6XXX,1,Set(CFWD=${CISCO_CALLFORWARD(${EXTEN})})
;    same => n,GotoIf($["${CFWD}" = ""]?ring)
;    same => n,NoOp(Forwarding ${EXTEN} -> ${CFWD})
;    same => n,Dial(Local/${CFWD}@from-internal,30)
;    same => n,Hangup()
;    same => n(ring),Dial(PJSIP/${EXTEN},30)
;    same => n,Voicemail(${EXTEN}@default,u)
;    same => n,Hangup()
;
; ----------------------------------------------------------------
; Recipe 4 — Hunt-group bulk toggle (close-of-business)
; ----------------------------------------------------------------
; Log everyone out of a hunt group at scheduled times. Function
; writes require a channel, so an external script originates a
; Local channel into an admin extension that runs the toggles
; in-dialplan. The bulkupdate REFER fires per Set() so each phone's
; HLog softkey state updates in lockstep.
;
;   exten => eob-logout,1,Set(CISCO_HUNTGROUP(6001)=no)
;    same => n,Set(CISCO_HUNTGROUP(6003)=no)
;    same => n,Set(CISCO_HUNTGROUP(6006)=no)
;    same => n,Set(CISCO_HUNTGROUP(6007)=no)
;    same => n,Hangup()
;
; Cron triggers it via Originate:
;
;   # /etc/cron.d/cisco-eob
;   0 18 * * 1-5 root /usr/sbin/asterisk -rx \
;       "channel originate Local/eob-logout@cisco-features application Hangup"
;
; Pair with CISCO_HUNTGROUP reads in your queue / hunt routing if
; you don't already rely on Asterisk's own queue agent state.
